tion between Prakrit and Sanskrit was at the center of an enduring "language order" in India, a set of ways of thinking about, naming, classifying, representing, and ultimately using languages. As a language of classical literature that nevertheless retained its associations with more demotic language practices, Prakrit both embodies major cultural tensions-between high and low, transregional and regional, cosmopolitan and vernacular-and provides a unique perspective onto the history of literature and culture in South Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLanguage and culturezIndia. 0aPrakrit languages. 0aPrakrit literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aSanskrit literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066755440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520968813?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520968813zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520968813/original  a978-3-11-064982-6 Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-066755-4 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA